<B>From:</B>           <A HREF="mailto:schramm@nufar.wisdom.weizmann.ac.il">schramm@nufar.wisdom.weizmann.ac.il</A> (Schramm Oded)
<B>Newsgroups:</B>     sci.math.research
<B>Subject:</B>        2 convex curves intersecting in 3 or more points
<B>Date:</B>           Mon, 18 Sep 1995 12:01:12 GMT
<B>Organization:</B>   Weizmann Institute of Science
<B>Summary:</B>        their curvatures are related
<B>Keywords:</B>       curvature
</PRE><HR><PRE>
Lemma:  Let g, h be two convex planar curves (sufficiently differentiable
so that the curvature is defined), which share at least 3 points. 
Then min k_g <U>&lt;</U> max k_h; that is, the minimum of the curvature of g
is at most the maximum of the curvature of h.

It is likely that this result is known.  If you recognize it, please 
inform me.

I have an elementary proof, and two nice applications,
related to conformal maps.

Oded Schramm            <A HREF="mailto:schramm@wisdom.weizmann.ac.il">schramm@wisdom.weizmann.ac.il</A>

